We want to sketch the solution without solving the equation. Hence, we
draw the phase space. Therefore, we first make a table with $\ Q$ and
the corresponding $dQ/dt$.

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}llllll@{}}
$\ Q=0$ & $\ Q=2$ & $\ Q=4$ & $\ Q=6$ & $\ Q=8$ & $\ Q=10$\\
$\ dQ/dt=5$ & $\ dQ/dt=4$ & $\ dQ/dt=3$ & $\ dQ/dt=2$ & $\ dQ/dt=1$ &
$\ dQ/dt=0$\\
\end{longtable}

After drawing the phase space, the curve of the solution can be plotted
by following the slopes.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MATH102_December_2012_Question_C_4_(c)_Image_1.png}
\caption{MATH102\_December\_2012\_Question\_C\_4\_\%28c\%29\_Image\_1.png}
\end{figure}
